Eric Gehringer -- Executive Vice President-Operations

Yes. And one of the greatest tools to do that is all of our continued efforts on train length. As we reported this morning, we're up 10%, 850 feet. But when you're thinking about the service product and being able to deliver that, one of the best tools you have is a very fluid network. As we think about 2.5 years ago, we would have had 800-ish trains running around in any given day. Now we're at 600, 605 a day. That's 25% less potential variability events, which is the primary driver for any degradation in trip plan compliance. So continuing to leverage train length on top of how we operate in our terminals, both key opportunities to consistently drive that number up to that mid- 80 number.

